raphic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice De Whixhall was born about 1240, in Whixall, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Wolfric De Whixall, was 23 and her mother, Mrs Wolfric De Whixhall, was 23. She married Ralph de Sandford in 1255, in Whixall, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died in Whitchurch, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1240–":"umbes 1240–Surnud","1240–Female":"1240–Surnud","1199–1250":"1199–1250","1256–1327":"1256–1327","1272–Male":"1272–Surnud","1274–1327":"1274–1327","1219–1311":"1219–1311","1218–Female":"1218–Surnud","1274":"1274","02 DEC 2003":"2. detsember 2003","1240":"1240","1272":"1272","1250":"1250","1239":"1239","1327":"1327","Abt 1240":"umbes 1240","1311":"1311","1256":"1256","1255":"1255","1199":"1199","about 1256":"umbes 1256","1219":"1219","1218":"1218","Sanford, Whitchurch, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Whitchurch, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom",